{
  "title": "Benchmarking Machine Learning Training Loops Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to use FastAPI, a modern, high-performance web framework for building APIs, in conjunction with Python 3.12+ to benchmark machine learning training loops.",
  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is used to create an API endpoint for executing and timing ML model training",
    "Python 3.12+'s new async/await syntax simplifies concurrent execution of multiple training runs",
    "Profiling tools like cProfile can be utilized to analyze the performance of each training run",
    "Utilizing FastAPI's built-in health check endpoint for ensuring the API is responsive during benchmarking"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, HealthCheck\nimport time\nimport cProfile\napp = FastAPI()\n\nmodel = YourModelClass()\n\n@app.get('/train', response_description='Train model and return training time')\nasync def train():\n    start_time = time.monotonic()\n    model.fit(X, y)\n    end_time = time.monotonic()\n    return {'training_time': end_time - start_time}\n\n@app.get('/health', response_model=HealthCheck)\nasync def health():\n    return HealthCheck(content={'status': 'ok'})\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    cProfile.run('app.train()')\n```"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+'s new async/await syntax allows for concurrent execution of multiple training runs",
    "FastAPI version >= 0.69.0 is required to use HealthCheck endpoint"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "This example assumes the existence of a machine learning model class named `YourModelClass` with `fit(X, y)` method",
    "For more accurate benchmarking, multiple training runs should be averaged",
    "In production scenarios, consider using specialized ML performance profiling libraries"
  ]
}
